00:28:45,413 --> 00:28:46,973
"why they may not be
lawfully joined together

499

00:28:47,053 --> 00:28:50,694
"let him now speak, or else hereafter
forever hold his peace."

500

00:28:57,453 --> 00:29:00,494
Do you realize you waive
all your legal rights in this marriage?

501

00:29:00,534 --> 00:29:02,574
Look, I signed all the papers, didn't I?

502

00:29:02,654 --> 00:29:04,014
You'll look after your wife on your own.

503

00:29:04,054 --> 00:29:05,934
The Air Force is not responsible.

504

00:29:06,574 --> 00:29:08,334
Yeah, I know.

505

00:29:08,414 --> 00:29:10,135
Romantic, ain't it, Major?

506

00:29:11,974 --> 00:29:13,894
Will you finish this ugly deed
and get it over?

507

00:29:15,254 --> 00:29:17,454
I now pronounce you man and wife.
Sign over there.

508

00:29:17,775 --> 00:29:19,295
Just a minute.

509

00:29:37,615 --> 00:29:39,256
That's it, Mrs. Kelly.

510
00:29:39,896 --> 00:29:41,616
Just you and me now.

511

00:29:52,617 --> 00:29:53,656
Where do we sign?

512

00:29:54,977 --> 00:29:57,137
May as well witness this now, Major.

513

00:29:57,496 --> 00:29:58,817
Yeah, all right.

514

00:30:01,458 --> 00:30:03,697
Incidentally, it was a great honor
meeting you, Major Gruver.

515

00:30:03,778 --> 00:30:04,817
Well, thank you.

516

00:30:05,657 --> 00:30:07,257
Say, tell me, Consul,

517

00:30:08,337 --> 00:30:10,858
are all these ceremonies
conducted like that?

518

00:30:11,097 --> 00:30:14,418
Well, we do our best
to prevent as many as possible.

519

00:30:15,138 --> 00:30:16,658
We make the paperwork so difficult,

520

00:30:16,738 --> 00:30:18,258
a good many of them lose steam.

521

00:30:18,298 --> 00:30:19,578
Uh-huh.

522

00:30:20,018 --> 00:30:22,179
Well, about how many, uh...

523

00:30:22,579 --> 00:30:25,618
About how many Gis have gone
through this ceremony?

524

00:30:26,819 --> 00:30:30,539
Oh, about 10,000.

525

00:30:31,339 --> 00:30:34,859
Ten thousand? Well, then,
you let a few slip by you, didn't you?

526

00:30:34,899 --> 00:30:35,979
A few, yes.

527

00:30:36,019 --> 00:30:36,979
Mmm-hmm.

528

00:30:38,419 --> 00:30:39,779
How's your girl, Major?

529

00:30:40,739 --> 00:30:42,099
Oh, Eileen?

530

00:30:42,419 --> 00:30:43,660
I haven't seen her in a couple days.

531

00:30:43,700 --> 00:30:46,899
I've been... You know, I've been moving in,
getting my things arranged.

532

00:30:48,060 --> 00:30:51,139
And she's been hightailing it
with the brass, socializing.

533
00:30:52,499 --> 00:30:53,700
Major,

534

00:30:53,780 --> 00:30:55,300
ain't you going to kiss the bride?

535

00:30:57,020 --> 00:30:58,501
Well, sure I'm going to kiss the bride!

536

00:31:00,141 --> 00:31:01,221
Yeah.

537

00:31:01,941 --> 00:31:02,940
Sure.

538

00:31:03,660 --> 00:31:07,180
Now, listen, I want you
to take good care of this boy, hear?

539

00:31:10,821 --> 00:31:13,301
Now, here's your ticket, honey.
Don't forget it.

540

00:31:15,741 --> 00:31:16,821
Okay, boy.

541

00:31:19,222 --> 00:31:20,501
Thanks, Major.

542

00:31:20,541 --> 00:31:22,141
Took a lot of guts for you
to come here today.

543

00:31:22,342 --> 00:31:23,702
Oh, quit.

544

00:31:23,941 --> 00:31:26,422
If you want anybody taken care of,
or need a job done

545

00:31:26,502 --> 00:31:27,862
that you West Point guys ain't allowed

546

00:31:27,942 --> 00:31:29,222
to do yourselves, I'm your man.

547

00:31:29,462 --> 00:31:31,782
Hold it. Now, I'm going to call on you, boy.

548

00:31:31,862 --> 00:31:32,942
Come on. Let's get a belt.

549

00:31:32,982 --> 00:31:33,982
All right.

550

00:31:34,662 --> 00:31:35,782
-Nice to see you.
- How are you, Lloyd, dear?

551

00:31:35,862 --> 00:31:37,542
Fine. Just fine.

552

00:31:37,622 --> 00:31:38,823
That's a pretty dress you got on.

553

00:31:38,902 --> 00:31:40,063
Thanks.

554

00:31:40,382 --> 00:31:41,943
Lloyd, sit down, son.

555

00:31:42,422 --> 00:31:43,503
All right.

556

00:31:47,143 --> 00:31:48,703
Thank you for coming over
so promptly, Lloyd.

557

00:31:48,783 --> 00:31:51,703
Well, that's all right.
I was just darning my socks.

558

00:31:51,783 --> 00:31:53,703
Lloyd, um...

559

00:31:54,983 --> 00:31:57,143
I don't know exactly how to put this.

560

00:31:57,184 --> 00:31:59,703
It's a little embarrassing, for me, that is.

561

00:32:00,784 --> 00:32:03,904
I understand you were a witness
at a marriage yesterday

562

00:32:04,024 --> 00:32:06,464
between one of your men
and a Japanese girl.

563

00:32:08,024 --> 00:32:11,264
Yeah, one man from my outfit in Korea.

564

00:32:12,025 --> 00:32:15,504
Well, you realize, of course,
there's an Army policy

565

00:32:15,544 --> 00:32:17,225
to discourage all such marriages.

566

00:32:17,824 --> 00:32:19,705
Yeah, well, I think they couldn't
have been discouraged.

567

00:32:19,785 --> 00:32:21,784
They're very much in love, and...

568

00:32:23,545 --> 00:32:25,065
I dare say.

569

00:32:25,505 --> 00:32:27,745
However, the fact that you personally

570

00:32:27,825 --> 00:32:28,945
seemed to sanction the marriage...

571

00:32:29,025 --> 00:32:32,505
Oh, no, no.
I didn't mean to give that impression at all.

572

00:32:32,586 --> 00:32:34,065
I didn't sanction it, and as a matter of fact,

573

00:32:34,106 --> 00:32:35,785
I tried to talk him out of it before.

574

00:32:36,065 --> 00:32:38,425
But, Lloyd, darling,
you did act as his witness.

575

00:32:39,946 --> 00:32:40,906
Well...

576

00:32:41,426 --> 00:32:43,386
You know, as long as
it's going to be inevitable,

577

00:32:43,466 --> 00:32:45,826
I thought I might as well try
to make it as pleasant as possible.

578

00:32:46,186 --> 00:32:48,186
Don't you see the position that puts me in?

579

00:32:48,586 --> 00:32:51,226
And since I'm the Area Commander here, I...

580

00:32:51,266 --> 00:32:53,946
No, you didn't do anything
to encourage this marriage, sir.

581

00:32:53,987 --> 00:32:56,066
I believe I did all this on my own.

582

00:32:56,147 --> 00:33:00,027
What do you mean on your own,
Lloyd, dear?

583

00:33:00,066 --> 00:33:02,267
Everything you do reflects on the General.

584

00:33:02,347 --> 00:33:04,267
After all, he is Eileen’s father.

585

00:33:05,027 --> 00:33:07,827
I'm afraid this places me in a position
of incompetence, Mrs. Webster,

586

00:33:07,867 --> 00:33:11,268
when it comes to, you know,
doing anything to help my own men.

587

00:33:12,307 --> 00:33:14,428
Let's stop beating around the bush.

588

00:33:14,788 --> 00:33:16,748
What's wrong between you and Eileen?

589

00:33:16,828 --> 00:33:19,428
You haven't been to see her
for several days.

590

00:33:23,508 --> 00:33:24,468
Well,

591

00:33:25,508 --> 00:33:28,748
you talked about
being embarrassed, sir, before.

592

00:33:29,068 --> 00:33:30,548
I'm embarrassed, too.

593

00:33:31,588 --> 00:33:34,589
- What about?
- Well, about my whole situation here.

594

00:33:35,149 --> 00:33:38,109
I'm a pilot, sir. I was doing a job in Korea.

595

00:33:38,149 --> 00:33:41,429
Unfinished job. Now, suddenly,
I'm pulled off that job and sent over here

596

00:33:41,469 --> 00:33:45,269
and plunked down at a desk
at this Interservice whatever it is,

597

00:33:45,309 --> 00:33:46,749
and, you know, where, as far as I can see,

598

00:33:46,829 --> 00:33:48,749
there's absolutely nothing to do.

599

00:33:48,830 --> 00:33:50,789
You know, all so as I can be with Eileen.

600

00:33:51,470 --> 00:33:53,110
There's nothing dishonest about it.

601

00:33:53,149 --> 00:33:55,030
That is, if you plan to get married.

602

00:33:55,469 --> 00:33:58,430
I think I know how Lloyd feels.

603

00:33:58,469 --> 00:34:00,270
Do you plan to get married or not?

604

00:34:00,350 --> 00:34:03,391
-Really, dear.
- Well, I'm her mother. I want to know.

605

00:34:05,871 --> 00:34:07,590
Well, Mrs. Webster,

606

00:34:07,670 --> 00:34:10,391
as of the moment,
Eileen isn't too sure about it.

607

00:34:10,710 --> 00:34:11,831
And I...

608

00:34:12,151 --> 00:34:14,711
Oh, we know, Lloyd, dear. Now, look.

609

00:34:15,231 --> 00:34:18,191
There's evidently been some
slight strain between you two,

610

00:34:18,271 --> 00:34:20,351
but don't let it become too important.

611

00:34:20,431 --> 00:34:23,111
Now, this is Sunday night.
Why don't you call her up later

612

00:34:23,191 --> 00:34:25,472
and ask her out to dinner or something?

613

00:34:25,671 --> 00:34:26,751
Well...

614

00:34:26,832 --> 00:34:29,471
Mother, I found the dearest little shop at...

615

00:34:30,552 --> 00:34:31,592
Hi, Lloyd.

616

00:34:31,992 --> 00:34:33,352
Hello, Eileen.

617

00:34:33,432 --> 00:34:35,552
Lloyd just came in to see you.

618

00:34:35,992 --> 00:34:37,432
-Oh?
- Oh, yeah.

619

00:34:39,032 --> 00:34:40,833
Listen...

620

00:34:41,952 --> 00:34:44,992
Listen, I thought
Sunday night, and I thought maybe

621

00:34:45,073 --> 00:34:47,793
you and I can go out
and catch a movie or something.

622

00:34:48,832 --> 00:34:50,113
Feel like it?

623

00:34:51,073 --> 00:34:54,432
I'm sorry, Lloyd.
I'm having dinner with some friends tonight.

624

00:34:54,713 --> 00:34:55,673
Well,

625

00:34:56,513 --> 00:34:57,993
what about tomorrow?

626

00:34:58,873 --> 00:35:00,594
That's booked, too, I'm afraid.

627

00:35:03,673 --> 00:35:06,273
Well, looks as though
I'm holding some pretty tough cards.

628

00:35:09,634 --> 00:35:12,034
What about next week?

629

00:35:13,634 --> 00:35:15,594
Of course, Lloyd. Call me?

630

00:35:18,474 --> 00:35:19,554
Okay-

631

00:35:22,834 --> 00:35:24,555
Mrs. Webster, General.

632

00:35:25,635 --> 00:35:26,595
Goodbye, Lloyd.

633

00:35:26,635 --> 00:35:28,355
- Bye, Eileen.
- Bye, Lloyd.

634

00:35:35,115 --> 00:35:38,156
Oh, Eileen. Why did you tell him
you were busy tonight?

635

00:35:40,756 --> 00:35:44,395
Because I don't want to see Lloyd Gruver
when you ask him to see me.

636

00:35:44,996 --> 00:35:46,116
Besides,

637

00:35:46,516 --> 00:35:48,195
I do have a date with that young Lieutenant

638

00:35:48,236 --> 00:35:50,115
and his wife from Fort Bragg.

639

00:35:50,156 --> 00:35:51,796
Whole bunch of us.

640

00:35:58,476 --> 00:36:00,637
I hope you don't lose my man for me.

641

00:36:22,077 --> 00:36:23,398
Boy, give me a martini, will you?

642

00:36:25,598 --> 00:36:27,198
Nope, make it lemonade.

643

00:36:28,958 --> 00:36:31,198
No, dog. Give me a scotch and soda.

644

00:36:32,038 --> 00:36:33,159
- Scotch and soda.
- -Yeah.

645

00:36:33,638 --> 00:36:35,278
Scotch and soda, sir.

646

00:36:35,558 --> 00:36:38,038
There's such a thing as insolence
through manner, you know.

647
00:36:44,999 --> 00:36:47,799
Well, I hate to admit it,
but I guess that's what I said.

648

00:36:49,959 --> 00:36:51,839
Well, I thought it sounded kind of strange

649

00:36:51,879 --> 00:36:54,159
coming from a guy
who shot down nine MiGs.

650

00:36:55,480 --> 00:36:56,760
Well, that's kind of a reflex action.

651

00:36:56,840 --> 00:36:58,439
I'm a West Point man, you know.

652

00:36:58,760 --> 00:37:01,480
I guess, it sneaks out sometimes.

653

00:37:04,520 --> 00:37:06,360
Now, listen, Captain, what does a fellow do

654

00:37:06,440 --> 00:37:08,360
around here after the sun goes down?

655

00:37:09,641 --> 00:37:10,640
Why?

656

00:37:11,040 --> 00:37:12,040
You on the loose?

657

00:37:12,361 --> 00:37:14,200
Uh... Halfway.

658

00:37:15,320 --> 00:37:16,680
Bring him another.

659

00:37:18,160 --> 00:37:20,321
What part of the South are you from?

660

00:37:21,121 --> 00:37:23,601
Almost any old place
that's got an Army post on it.

661

00:37:25,321 --> 00:37:28,041
I was all set to take the exams at West Point

662

00:37:28,321 --> 00:37:30,281
and there was a teacher there

663

00:37:30,961 --> 00:37:33,362
who made me take a part in a school play.

664

00:37:33,642 --> 00:37:36,882
They were doing one of those
Hungarian things by Molnar.

665

00:37:38,761 --> 00:37:40,682
You never did hear a Hungarian play

666

00:37:40,722 --> 00:37:42,602
played in a Southern accent, did you?

667

00:37:42,922 --> 00:37:44,482
No, I'm afraid I missed that.

668

00:37:44,522 --> 00:37:47,162
That's a shame,
because I was awful good in it.

669

00:37:47,842 --> 00:37:51,723
Anyhow, I suddenly didn't want
to go to West Point

670

00:37:52,563 --> 00:37:54,603
and didn't want
to have anything to do with it.

671

00:37:54,682 --> 00:37:56,883
And my mother come up to the school,

672

00:37:58,323 --> 00:38:01,003
and she said,
"We always expected you to go to the Point

673

00:38:01,083 --> 00:38:03,883
"like your father and his father before him."

674

00:38:04,203 --> 00:38:06,363
And I told her,

675

00:38:06,443 --> 00:38:10,804
I said I had an idea about
a whole different way of life.

676

00:38:11,604 --> 00:38:12,883
What did she say to that?

677

00:38:13,684 --> 00:38:15,564
She said something like,

678

00:38:16,444 --> 00:38:18,204
"If I ever once had that idea,

679

00:38:18,284 --> 00:38:20,604
"I shouldn't let anything stop me."

680

00:38:21,564 --> 00:38:26,124
And she couldn't come right out and say,
"Don't go to the Point."

681

00:38:26,165 --> 00:38:28,124
You know, but I know what she meant.

682

00:38:29,244 --> 00:38:31,645
Then, of course,
my father flew up from Texas and...

683
00:38:32,084 --> 00:38:33,165
He put you straight, huh?

684

00:38:34,085 --> 00:38:36,884
No, he just looked at me and said,

685

00:38:36,965 --> 00:38:39,965
"If you don't want to go to the Point,
don't go to the Point.

686

00:38:40,045 --> 00:38:42,565
"The unhappiest men I know are those

687

00:38:44,085 --> 00:38:47,485
"who are forced into something
they got no inaptitude for."

688

00:38:47,885 --> 00:38:50,485
How did he force you to go to the Point?

689

00:38:51,045 --> 00:38:53,526
That's what I'm telling you.
He didn't force me. He just...

690

00:38:53,606 --> 00:38:56,686
We just had a little talk,
and he flew back to Texas

691

00:38:56,726 --> 00:38:58,766
and I went on to the Point.

692

00:39:00,327 --> 00:39:01,446
I see.

693

00:39:02,006 --> 00:39:04,646
Well, uh, I'll tell you
something though, Mike.

694

00:39:06,126 --> 00:39:09,447
I never once had any regrets
about going to the Point.

695

00:39:10,167 --> 00:39:11,967
Except, just lately,

696

00:39:12,327 --> 00:39:15,007
I've had some old feeling come back on me.

697

00:39:15,847 --> 00:39:17,367
I don't know if I want to go on

698

00:39:17,447 --> 00:39:20,247
in the Air Force and buck for a star

699

00:39:20,327 --> 00:39:22,367
and get married in the Webster family

700

00:39:22,447 --> 00:39:24,687
and get swallowed up by all that.

701

00:39:26,447 --> 00:39:28,848
I think maybe my old lady was right.

702

00:39:30,368 --> 00:39:32,167
Well, what does it all mean?

703

00:39:33,848 --> 00:39:36,528
Eternal struggle, sex,

704

00:39:37,528 --> 00:39:39,088
New York Yankees.

705

00:39:39,528 --> 00:39:41,848
All right. Quit, now. Come on.

706

00:39:50,769 --> 00:39:52,929
Isn't that a nice-looking bridge?

707

00:39:53,008 --> 00:39:54,689
Yeah,
that's the Bitchi-Bashi.

708

00:39:55,049 --> 00:39:56,049
Say what?

709

00:39:56,089 --> 00:39:57,729
The Bitchi-Bashi.

710

00:39:57,809 --> 00:40:00,009
Bashi is Japanese for "bridge."

711

00:40:00,049 --> 00:40:02,649
We call this particular one the Bitchi-Bashi

712

00:40:02,730 --> 00:40:06,010
because there's so much
lovely stuff that goes over it.

713

00:40:07,250 --> 00:40:08,850
Did you say stuff?

714

00:40:09,490 --> 00:40:11,249
Brother, I said stuff.

715

00:40:12,890 --> 00:40:16,290
Will you kindly tell me what
we're standing in the bushes for?

716

00:40:16,370 --> 00:40:18,450
-Can't touch it.
- Why not?

717

00:40:18,530 --> 00:40:22,451
Well, you see, these girls that go over there
are the Matsubayashi girls.

718

00:40:22,690 --> 00:40:24,730
They just cross over there
on the way to the theater

719

00:40:24,811 --> 00:40:27,731
from those cells over there,
those dormitories.

720

00:40:28,171 --> 00:40:30,451
Oh, that's right.
Somebody told me about that.

721

00:40:32,331 --> 00:40:35,571
Hey, boy, is that anything
going over there now?

722

00:40:38,451 --> 00:40:40,452
Hey, come on.
The goods are on display.

723

00:40:40,891 --> 00:40:42,612
Wait for me, buddy.

724

00:41:10,933 --> 00:41:13,533
There's Fumiko-san.
The one you saw me with.

725

00:41:13,613 --> 00:41:15,333
- Yeah. The little one in pink.
- Yeah, that's the one.

726

00:41:19,053 --> 00:41:20,974
You're not going over there and say hello?

727

00:41:21,014 --> 00:41:24,054
What, in public?
A Matsubayashi girl? Are you nuts?

728

00:41:24,094 --> 00:41:26,374
Well, you take her to the officers‘ club.

729

00:41:26,454 --> 00:41:28,254
Well, that's for Americans.

730

00:41:28,334 --> 00:41:31,254
Thought I could sneak her in there
without her being recognized.

731

00:41:31,694 --> 00:41:33,655
What happens if they catch them?

732

00:41:33,734 --> 00:41:35,334
Immediate dismissal.

733

00:41:35,415 --> 00:41:37,014
- No fooling?
- Yeah.

734

00:41:37,055 --> 00:41:39,775
No Matsubayashi girl
is allowed to have dates of any kind.

735

00:41:40,414 --> 00:41:42,135
You were dating her, you.

736

00:41:42,454 --> 00:41:44,415
Yeah, well, I'm different.

737

00:41:45,495 --> 00:41:46,575
Oh, get out of here.

738

00:41:46,615 --> 00:41:48,855
Well, like I told President Truman,

739

00:41:48,935 --> 00:41:51,935
"Harry, you was wrong
when you sold the Marines short."

